Simonâ€™s Fish Gut Content: SAP Evaluation

Evan Krell

August 10, 2017

Statistical Assignment Package (SAP) was used for taxonomic assignment of the gut contents of several Gulf of Mexico species. These samples were collected by Jim Simonsâ€™ lab and processed by the Genomics Core Lab.

The companion script evaluateSAP/evaluateSAP.py has been used to quantify several attributes related to the SAP results. The goal is to analyze this table to learn which assignments are plausible and what factors affect the ability to make a species-level assignment.

SAP was run with the default parameters. The most important parameters are these:

Parameter Selected Description
Assignment Barcoder A Bayesian method for taxonomic assignment that used Markov chain monte carlo.
Posterior Probability Cutoff 0.95 Only report assignments with posterior probability at least 0.95
Min Significance 10 â€œLower E-value bound for accepting homologue sequencesâ€
Significance 50 â€œE-value cutoff for significant hits.â€
Min Identity 0.5 â€œMinimum global alignment similarity of best blast hit.â€
Best Hits 30 â€œMaximal number of homologues to add to alignment purely based on significant E-value.â€

Command used:

  sap --project Exp2 --database ../nr_mito.SAP2.fasta \
      --minidentity 0.97 --significance 0.5 \
      ../SAPexplore-OTU.fasta
